{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775868731409,"sessionID":"ses_285fa8df0ffeLn6Q7UsZ3LEyZT","part":{"id":"prt_d7a059e61001nfUHEzNpXVbVsK","messageID":"msg_d7a0585ab001RaKr3ZMcPBJaX2","sessionID":"ses_285fa8df0ffeLn6Q7UsZ3LEyZT","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_functions.write:1","state":{"status":"error","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/proposal.md","content":"# Proposal: Valkey Storage Implementation (AR-014)\n\n## Metadata\n\n| Field | Value |\n|-------|-------|\n| **AR** | AR-014 |\n| **Module** | pkg/store |\n| **Language** | Go |\n| **Size** | S |\n| **Status** | Proposed |\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nImplement a Valkey storage backend for the session store module (`pkg/store`) to provide an alternative to the existing Redis implementation. This enables deployment flexibility, allowing operators to choose between Redis or Valkey as the underlying storage engine for sandbox metadata persistence.\n\nThe Valkey implementation will:\n- Maintain full compatibility with the existing `Store` interface contract\n- Provide identical functionality for session CRUD operations, expiry tracking, and garbage collection\n- Support the same sorted-set based indexing for expiry and last-activity tracking\n- Enable seamless backend selection via the `STORE_TYPE` environment variable\n\n---\n\n## Scope\n\n### In Scope\n\n1. **Valkey Store Implementation** (`store_valkey.go`)\n   - Implement all `Store` interface methods: `Ping`, `GetSandboxBySessionID`, `StoreSandbox`, `UpdateSandbox`, `DeleteSandboxBySessionID`, `ListExpiredSandboxes`, `ListInactiveSandboxes`, `UpdateSessionLastActivity`, `Close`\n   - Use `github.com/valkey-io/valkey-go` client library\n   - Maintain same key patterns as Redis (`session:`, `session:expiry`, `session:last_activity`)\n   - Implement atomic multi-command operations using `DoMulti`\n\n2. **Configuration & Environment**\n   - `VALKEY_ADDR` (comma-separated list of addresses)\n   - `VALKEY_PASSWORD` with `VALKEY_PASSWORD_REQUIRED` option\n   - `VALKEY_DISABLE_CACHE` and `VALKEY_FORCE_SINGLE` client options\n   - `STORE_TYPE=valkey` selector (case-insensitive)\n\n3. **Provider Selection Logic** (`singleton.go`)\n   - Extend `initStore()` to support `\"valkey\"` as a valid `STORE_TYPE` value\n   - Maintain backward compatibility with default `\"redis\"` selection\n\n4. **Error Handling**\n   - Map Valkey nil responses to `ErrNotFound`\n   - Preserve same error semantics as Redis implementation\n\n### Out of Scope\n\n- Changes to `Store` interface definition\n- Modifications to `SandboxInfo` type or serialization format\n- New features beyond existing Redis functionality\n- Migration tooling between Redis and Valkey backends\n- Changes to client-go or other packages\n\n---\n\n## Impact Analysis\n\n### Positive Impacts\n\n| Area | Impact |\n|------|--------|\n| **Deployment Flexibility** | Operators can choose Valkey as an open-source, high-performance alternative to Redis without code changes |\n| **Vendor Neutrality** | Reduces dependency on Redis-specific implementations; Valkey is a Linux Foundation project with open governance |\n| **Performance** | Valkey's multi-threaded architecture may offer improved throughput for high-concurrency scenarios |\n| **Compatibility** | Zero-downtime backend switching via configuration only; same data model and key patterns |\n| **Risk Mitigation** | Provides fallback options if Redis licensing or availability concerns arise |\n\n### Risks and Mitigations\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|------|------------|--------|------------|\n| Valkey client library differences | Low | Medium | Thorough testing against existing test suite; handle `IsValkeyNil` vs Redis `Nil` |\n| MGET slot alignment requirements | Low | Low | Document deployment consideration for clustered setups; use hashtag patterns if needed |\n| Dependency maintenance | Low | Low | Valkey Go client is actively maintained by Valkey IO project |\n| Configuration complexity | Low | Low | Clear documentation of environment variables; validation at startup |\n\n### Affected Components\n\n```\npkg/store/\n├── singleton.go          (extend initStore to support valkeyStoreType)\n└── store_valkey.go       (NEW - Valkey implementation)\n```\n\n### Dependencies\n\n- **New**: `github.com/valkey-io/valkey-go` (add to go.mod)\n- **Existing**: `github.com/redis/go-redis/v9` (unchanged)\n- **Existing**: `k8s.io/klog/v2` (for Valkey options logging)\n\n---\n\n## Alternatives Considered\n\n### Alternative 1: Unified Client Abstraction\n\n**Description**: Create a generic KV client wrapper that abstracts both Redis and Valkey behind a common internal interface.\n\n**Decision**: **Rejected**\n\n**Rationale**:\n- Adds unnecessary complexity and abstraction overhead\n- Both clients have different API shapes and response types\n- Current approach of separate implementations is clearer and easier to maintain\n- `sync.Once` singleton pattern already provides clean provider selection\n\n### Alternative 2: Protocol-Level Compatibility (Redis Commands on Valkey)\n\n**Description**: Use Redis client (`go-redis`) to connect to Valkey server since Valkey maintains Redis protocol compatibility.\n\n**Decision**: **Rejected**\n\n**Rationale**:\n- While Valkey is Redis-compatible at the protocol level, using native Valkey client provides:\n  - Better performance optimizations specific to Valkey architecture\n  - Access to Valkey-specific features if needed in future\n  - Clearer dependency semantics (Valkey client → Valkey server)\n- Native client handles connection pooling, pipelining, and clustering with Valkey-specific optimizations\n\n### Alternative 3: Plugin Architecture\n\n**Description**: Define a plugin interface allowing external storage backends to be loaded dynamically.\n\n**Decision**: **Rejected** (Future consideration)\n\n**Rationale**:\n- Over-engineering for current requirements (only 2 backends)\n- Adds complexity of dynamic loading, versioning, and lifecycle management\n- Go's static compilation model makes dynamic plugins less idiomatic\n- Can be revisited if 3+ storage backends become necessary\n\n### Alternative 4: Continue with Redis Only\n\n**Description**: Do not implement Valkey support; maintain Redis as the sole backend.\n\n**Decision**: **Rejected**\n\n**Rationale**:\n- Valkey adoption is growing in the cloud-native ecosystem\n- Some organizations have strategic preferences for Valkey due to licensing or governance\n- Implementation cost is low (small module, well-defined interface)\n- Provides operational flexibility without significant maintenance burden\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Notes\n\n### Key Design Decisions\n\n1. **Same Key Patterns**: Valkey uses identical key prefix and ZSET naming to ensure data portability between backends\n2. **MGET for Batch Loading**: Uses `Mget` for loading multiple sandboxes; documented that keys should be in same slot for clustered deployments\n3. **Score Semantics**: Unix timestamp (seconds since epoch) as float64 score for ZSET ordering, identical to Redis\n4. **Atomic Operations**: `DoMulti` for pipeline-like atomicity on write operations\n\n### Testing Strategy\n\n- Unit tests following same patterns as `store_redis.go` tests\n- Integration tests with Valkey container (similar to Redis tests)\n- Verify `ErrNotFound` semantics via `IsValkeyNil`\n- Validate environment variable parsing and client option building\n\n---\n\n## Timeline\n\n| Phase | Duration | Deliverables |\n|-------|----------|--------------|\n| Implementation | 1 day | `store_valkey.go`, `singleton.go` updates |\n| Unit Tests | 0.5 day | Test coverage for all Store methods |\n| Integration Tests | 0.5 day | Container-based Valkey tests |\n| Documentation | 0.5 day | Environment variable reference, deployment notes |\n| **Total** | **2.5 days** | |\n\n---\n\n## Approval\n\n| Role | Name | Date | Decision |\n|------|------|------|----------|\n| Author | - | - | Proposed |\n| Reviewer | - | - | Pending |\n| Approver | - | - | Pending |\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n- `session-store/design.md` - Store interface and Redis implementation details\n- `session-store/spec.md` - Complete specification for Store behavior\n- `deployment/client-go.md` - Project context (agentcube v1alpha1 API)\n- Valkey Go Client: https://github.com/valkey-io/valkey-go\n"},"error":"You must read file /home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/proposal.md before overwriting it. Use the Read tool first","time":{"start":1775868731395,"end":1775868731404}}}}
